1. Definitions.

   a. "Canonical Sponsor Feed" means the sponsor-feed endpoint configured by
      default in the Hanji release you received, a successor endpoint publicly
      designated by the Hanji project, or a mirror expressly authorized by the
      Hanji copyright holders. An operator-selected or replacement feed is not
      a Canonical Sponsor Feed merely because it uses the same data format.

   b. "Faithful Sponsor Relay" means the sponsor-feed functionality shipped
      with Hanji that retrieves the Canonical Sponsor Feed — or, when the
      deployment is configured for offline operation, reads the Bundled Sponsor
      Snapshot — and relays its sponsor names and links without substitution,
      suppression, reordering, or addition. Transport security checks, safe URL
      normalization, bounded parsing, caching, and limiting the result to the
      shipped number of sponsor slots do not make a relay unfaithful.

   c. "Sponsor Banner Feature" means both the Faithful Sponsor Relay and the
      sign-in-screen sponsor banner component that renders its result, in
      substantially their shipped form, presentation, and placement. The
      shipped banner may present the relayed sponsors individually or in
      rotation — for example, a single sponsor chosen when the sign-in screen
      loads — and such presentation is part of its shipped form; qualification
      does not require any particular number of sponsors to be visible at once.

   d. A "Qualifying Version" is the Hanji Materials, with or without
      modifications or combination with other code, in which the Sponsor
      Banner Feature is present, functional, enabled by default for the
      deployment and for new users, and not removed, replaced, redirected,
      disabled, suppressed, obscured, or made materially less prominent than
      its shipped form.

   e. "Object Code" and "Corresponding Source" have the meanings given in
      AGPL-3.0. Object Code expressly includes compiled, minified, transpiled,
      or bundled browser code such as JavaScript, CSS, WebAssembly, source
      maps when supplied, and other frontend assets generated from source.

   f. "Bundled Sponsor Snapshot" means the sponsor snapshot data file shipped
      in the Hanji release you received, used unmodified. It lets a deployment
      show sponsors without making the network request to the Canonical Sponsor
      Feed (for example on a closed network, or to avoid the outbound request).
      An operator-edited, replaced, or externally-substituted snapshot is not a
      Bundled Sponsor Snapshot, exactly as a replacement feed is not a
      Canonical Sponsor Feed.

2. Qualifying operation.

   A version qualifies only while it retrieves the Canonical Sponsor Feed
   through the Faithful Sponsor Relay and runs the Sponsor Banner Feature,
   unmodified in its sponsor fetch-and-display behavior, on the ordinary
   sign-in screen, so that the feed's sponsors are shown to users through that
   shipped feature. Qualification depends on keeping that sponsor fetch-and-
   display code present, unmodified in behavior, and enabled by default — not
   on any particular number of sponsors being visible at once or on a
   particular visual arrangement. A deployment-wide setting, policy,
   stylesheet, routing change, proxy, or other mechanism that hides, bypasses,
   replaces, modifies, or disables the feature prevents qualification.

   A deployment may instead operate in an offline mode that displays the
   Bundled Sponsor Snapshot through the Sponsor Banner Feature rather than
   retrieving the Canonical Sponsor Feed over the network; such a version
   qualifies while it displays that snapshot unmodified through the feature.
   Editing, replacing, or externally substituting the Bundled Sponsor Snapshot
   is unfaithful and prevents qualification, exactly as substituting the live
   feed would.

   An empty response from the Canonical Sponsor Feed, or a temporary feed or
   network failure outside the operator's reasonable control, does not by
   itself prevent qualification, provided that the canonical configuration and the
   unmodified fetch-and-display path remain enabled, the operator does not
   cause or prolong the failure, and normal display resumes automatically when
   the Canonical Sponsor Feed becomes available.

